-- U.S.-based stock funds attract $5.4 bln in latest week - Lipper
-- By Sam Forgione
-- Thu Apr 03, 2014 05:09PM EDT
-- None



NEW YORK, April 3 (Reuters) - Investors in U.S.-based funds poured $5.4 billion into stock funds in the week ended April 2, marking the biggest inflows into the funds in three weeks, data from Thomson Reuters' Lipper service showed on Thursday.

Funds that specialize in emerging market stocks attracted $2.7 billion of the net inflows, marking the biggest inflows into the funds since Jan. 2013.  Taxable bond funds attracted $3.7 billion in new cash, marking their fourth straight week of inflows. Emerging market bond funds attracted $508.3 million in inflows, marking their biggest inflows since May 2013.  Riskier high-yield bond funds attracted $493 million, reversing the prior week's outflows, while low-risk money market funds posted $15.7 billion in outflows, marking their fifth straight week of withdrawals. Commodities and precious metals funds, which mainly invest in gold futures, posted $301.3 million in outflows, marking their first outflows in six weeks.